#compdef oramacore
# ============================================================================
# oramacore - OramaCore: full-stack runtime for AI answer engines (Rust, AGPL-3.0)
#
# Author : Orama Search team
# Upstream: https://github.com/oramasearch/oramacore
#
# OramaCore is the all-in-one Rust runtime that powers
# Orama's hosted AI answer-engine and on-prem retrieval
# stack. Bundles: a vector + BM25 + faceted lexical search
# index (Tantivy-style segment design), a retrieval-augmented
# generation orchestrator (chunk + embed + retrieve + rerank
# + generate), an embedded LLM-call layer (OpenAI / Anthropic
# / local via Ollama + vLLM passthrough), a tiktoken-based
# token counter for cost / budget gating, a tree-sitter-based
# code chunker for codebase ingestion, and a CPython embed
# (pyo3) for the per-pipeline transform hooks.
#
# Usage:
#   oramacore                            - start the runtime, read
#                                          ./config.yaml (override via
#                                          CONFIG_PATH env var)
#   load_transcripts                     - companion ingest tool
#                                          (separate binary, hidden from
#                                          this completion)
#
# No CLI flags - all configuration is YAML driven. The
# config file controls:
#   - HTTP/gRPC listen addresses
#   - vector store path + segment policy
#   - per-tenant API keys + quotas
#   - embedding provider + model + dimensions
#   - LLM provider + model + max-tokens
#   - tracing destinations (OTLP / Jaeger / Sentry)
#
# Configuration overrides:
#   CONFIG_PATH=<file>     - YAML config path (default ./config.yaml)
#   ORAMACORE_<KEY>=<val>  - per-key config override
#                            (e.g. ORAMACORE_HTTP_PORT=8080)
#
# The backoff lane is built on `backoff = "0.4.0"` with the
# `tokio` feature (declared verbatim at upstream Cargo.toml
# HEAD), the canonical Rust exponential-backoff retry
# library by Tomasz Kurcz (ihrwein) - github.com/ihrwein/
# backoff, 350+ stars. The crate is the Rust port of Cenk
# Altı's Go `cenkalti/backoff` library, with the same
# `ExponentialBackoff` policy (initial interval + multiplier
# + max-interval + max-elapsed-time + jitter) and the same
# `retry / retry_notify` operator combinators. OramaCore
# uses it to gate retries against the upstream LLM API +
# embedding API calls - both fail in characteristic patterns
# (429 rate-limit, 503 capacity, transient timeouts) that
# benefit from idempotent retry with exponential backoff
# rather than immediate failure.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 233 :: Exponential-backoff retry policies (idempotent retry gates)
# Round 1397 :: Rust slot 1 of 4 :: OPENS Axis 233
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis (proposed):
#   Rust    : ihrwein/backoff              - Rust port of cenkalti/backoff
#   Go      : cenkalti/backoff             - de-facto Go exponential backoff
#                                            (the *original* implementation;
#                                             every other lane traces back
#                                             to Cenk Altı's 2014 Go crate)
#   TS/Node : vercel/async-retry           - canonical Node retry combinator
#                                            (alternative: tim-kos/node-retry
#                                             is the underlying retry policy
#                                             machinery)
#
# Exponential backoff retry is one of the rare axes where
# the *canonical algorithm* originates in a single specific
# Go library and was ported across to other languages. Cenk
# Altı authored cenkalti/backoff in 2014 implementing the
# Google SRE book's exponential-backoff-with-jitter pattern;
# ihrwein/backoff is the line-by-line Rust port, sometimes
# branded as "the Rust port of cenkalti/backoff" in the
# README. The Node lane diverged more - vercel/async-retry
# is API-similar but implementation-distinct.
#
# Use-case alignment in this axis: every lane targets the
# same operational pattern - "I have an HTTP/RPC call to an
# external service that fails intermittently with retryable
# status codes; retry with exponential backoff + jitter,
# bail after max-elapsed-time or non-retryable status."
# OramaCore wraps every external LLM/embedding/storage call
# in `backoff::future::retry` to gate against rate-limit and
# transient-failure responses.
# ============================================================================

_oramacore() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[print help]' \
        '(- *)--version[print version]'
}

_oramacore "$@"
